- ts: 2026-04-23T00:45:12Z
  event: clarify_critic
  feature: investigate-daytime-pipeline-blockers-subprocess-auth-task-selection-re-runs-completed-tasks
  findings:
    - "Intent clarity rated High citing 'root-cause both, land fixes or follow-up tickets,' but the source leaves fix-vs-ticket per-finding with no decision rule (no complexity threshold, no time-box, no coupling criterion). Intent is conditional on an un-specified executor judgment."
    - "Intent clarity reinforced by 'exact reproduction given,' but only Problem 2 has a reproduction recipe. Problem 1 has a bug restatement ('reproduces on any pipeline run from an interactive session without explicit auth env propagation'), not a repro procedure — no command, no expected-vs-actual contract."
    - "Scope boundedness rated High, but 'enumerated in-scope' overstates the source: in-scope is two bullets (one a negative constraint), with no bounds on which subsystems may be touched — runner.sh modifications, SDK-internal forks, CLI-flag additions, and credentials.json handling are all undetermined."
    - "'Bounded per-finding decision, not a scope gap' is the orchestrator's gloss, not the source's claim. Without a decision rule, every finding's fix-vs-ticket routing is a mini-scope question — bounded choices are not the same as bounded criteria."
    - "Requirements alignment High rests on multi-agent.md:84 naming ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, but the ticket itself lists that key as one of three 'possible lines of investigation' — the source frames the auth vector as open. A requirements line naming a variable does not make alignment 'High'; it establishes topic relevance only."
    - "'requirements/pipeline.md covers dispatch / task selection' is asserted without line reference or quoted passage. pipeline.md talks about feature-level statuses (pending/running/merged/paused), not task-level [x] checkbox semantics. 'Covers' is topic overlap, not normative alignment."
    - "Complexity rated 'complex' treats Problem 2 as a single unit, but the source presents three alternative hypotheses ('not calling _parse_field_status at all,' 'calling it but ignoring done result,' 'stale or different plan.md') with radically different fix profiles. The rating doesn't acknowledge the variance the source itself telegraphs."
    - "Criticality 'high' cites 'shared harness infrastructure,' but the source notes the overnight runner works and lifecycle 100 'can be hand-finished by invoking probe-apparatus.sh directly' — a documented manual workaround. The daytime pipeline is one mode among several; 'blocks the core dispatch path' overstates severity."
  dispositions:
    apply: 3
    dismiss: 3
    ask: 2
  applied_fixes:
    - "Revised scope boundedness from High to Medium — source does not enumerate which subsystems may be modified and provides no decision rule for fix-vs-follow-up routing; scope-boundedness is Medium against the source, not High."
    - "Revised requirements alignment from High to Partial — multi-agent.md:84 and pipeline.md provide topic coverage but no normative constraint on the auth vector or the [x]-skip task-selection contract; alignment is topic-relevant, not normative."
  dismissals:
    - finding_index: 1
      rationale: "Conflates research readiness with intent clarity. Problem 1's reproduction gap is a research-phase concern; the intent statement ('fix subprocess auth propagation in the daytime pipeline so SDK-spawned agents inherit the parent session's auth') is clear without an executable repro recipe. Research can instrument a pipeline run to reproduce."
    - finding_index: 6
      rationale: "Complexity tier is an upper-bound gate for Plan/Review scaling. Even if Problem 2's true cause is the simplest hypothesis (one-line wiring fix), the combined two-subsystem investigation (SDK auth path + pipeline task-selection path) plus cross-cutting behavioral effects satisfy clarify.md §5 complex-tier criteria. Tier holds."
    - finding_index: 7
      rationale: "Clarify.md §5: 'Default to high for skill/lifecycle/hook/workflow changes. Default to medium only for clearly isolated, easily-reverted tooling changes.' The daytime pipeline is shared workflow infrastructure under active iteration, not an isolated tweak; probe-apparatus.sh is a per-lifecycle manual workaround, not a systemic fallback. The High default holds."
  status: ok
